The Learner's Guide to AI Agent Memory: Keyword vs. Semantic Search

1. The "Amnesia" Problem: Why Agents Need Search

At their core, Large Language Models (LLMs) are stateless. This means they do not possess a biological brain that learns from every interaction in real-time. Instead, every API call is a "cold start."

Defining Statelessness In AI architecture, "stateless" means that every request to the model is a fresh event. The LLM does not "remember" the previous sentence unless it is manually fed back into the prompt. Without an external system to manage this, the agent effectively lives in a state of permanent amnesia.

To bridge this gap, engineers use a Virtual Memory analogy. Think of the LLM’s Context Window as RAM—it is fast, expensive, and extremely limited in space. Sending an entire conversation history every time is like trying to run an entire database in RAM; it leads to high costs, increased latency, and eventually "context exhaustion" where the model forgets the beginning of the talk. To scale, we need a Disk—an external storage system—and a way to "page" relevant information back into the LLM's active mind.


