2. Keyword Search: Finding the Exact Needle

Keyword search is the "literal" method of retrieval. It is the architectural equivalent of a magnifying glass. In high-performance systems like Claude Code, this is often handled by grep, while local-first agents like OpenClaw use the SQLite FTS5 (Full-Text Search) extension.

Keyword search functions at two distinct levels:

1. Literal Matching: The system scans for an exact sequence of characters. This is non-negotiable for finding specific technical identifiers like UUIDs, Git hashes, or CSS class names (e.g., useState).
2. Relevance Ranking (BM25): Professional systems use the BM25 algorithm. Instead of just finding a match, it ranks results by factoring in "Term Frequency" (how often a word appears) and "Inverse Document Frequency" (how unique the word is across all your data).

The "So What?": If you are searching for a specific error code like connection_refused_0x44, a conceptual search might fail you. Literal matching ensures that technical precision is maintained. However, because it is "literal," it misses synonyms—it will find "speed" but ignore "velocity."


